df_loan.shape
## 3. Define the target variable

We only keep loans with a resolved outcome — `Fully Paid`, `Charged Off`, or `Default` — and drop loans still in progress (e.g. `Current`), which have no settled outcome to learn from.
resolved_mask = df_loan["loan_status"].isin(["Fully Paid", "Charged Off", "Default"])
df_loan = df_loan[resolved_mask]
df_loan["loan_status"].value_counts()
def create_target(status: str) -> int:
    """1 = the loan went bad (Charged Off / Default), 0 = Fully Paid."""
    return 0 if status == "Fully Paid" else 1


df_loan["Late_Loan"] = df_loan["loan_status"].map(create_target)
print(df_loan["Late_Loan"].value_counts())
print(f"Base default rate: {df_loan['Late_Loan'].mean():.3%}")
## 4. Drop sparse and leaky columns

First remove any column missing more than 10% of its values, then drop columns that either have no predictive intuition (`id`, `url`, `zip_code`, ...) or that leak the outcome (`total_pymnt`, `recoveries`, `last_pymnt_amnt`, ... — these are only known *after* a loan has already resolved, so a model trained on them would be cheating).
missing_share = df_loan.isnull().mean()
sparse_cols = missing_share[missing_share > 0.10].index.tolist()
df_loan = df_loan.drop(columns=sparse_cols)
df_loan.shape
leaky_or_irrelevant = [
    "id", "member_id", "loan_status", "url", "zip_code", "policy_code",
    "application_type", "last_pymnt_d", "last_credit_pull_d",
    "verification_status", "pymnt_plan", "funded_amnt", "funded_amnt_inv",
